are the product of rough compromise struck by  contending groups within the
democratic process. When they touch upon an individual's race  or ethnic
background, he is entitled to a judicial determination that the burden he is 
asked to bear on that basis is precisely tailored  to serve a compelling
governmental interest. The Constitution guarantees that right to  every person
regardless of his background.&quot;  
<CITE><U>Adarand Constructors, Inc. v. Pena</U></CITE>, 115 S. Ct.  2097
