<P>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<A NAME="118"><B>118</B></A>					See <U>1994
Catalog of Federal Domestic  Assistance</U>, &quot;Special Emphasis Outreach 
Program Grants,&quot; Program ID 10.140. In FY 1995,  this program was expected
to receive $100,000.
</P>
<P>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<A NAME="119"><B>119</B></A>					One such
questionable program is the  Bureau of Indian Affairs' Higher Education Grant
Program, which received an appropriation  of $29.8 million in FY 1995. This
program provides up to $7,450 per year to college  students who belong to Indian
tribes &quot;to supplement  the total financial aid package prepared [for the
student] by the college financial aid officer.&quot;   Thus, two students from
identical socioeconomic backgrounds would receive  dramatically different levels
of federal assistance to  attend college, with the only difference between the
two being that one is &quot;at least  onefourth degree Indian blood descendent&quot;
and owns  a &quot;certificate of Indian blood.&quot;  See 
<U>1994 Catalog of Federal Domestic Assistance</U>,  Program ID15.114. There is
some evidence to  suggest that many Americans with trace levels of  Indian
ancestry have taken advantage of these preferences. Demographic trends, for 
example, cannot explain the threefold increase in  the number of Americans
identifying themselves as American Indians since the 1960 census.  Ac
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 16 -->  cording to <U>The New York Times</U>
for March 5, 1991, &quot;the growing realization that an  Indian heritage can
mean special benefits has motivated many Indians, and presumably some 
impostors, to openly assert an Indian background.&quot;   One California
contractor won a $19 million contract on the Los Angeles rapid transit  system
because he was onesixtyfourth American Indian. See Roberts and Stratton, 
<U>The New Color Line</U>, p. 158.
</P>

