<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Chapter 14: Federalism: Additional Information - Heritage</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<center>
<h2>Issues '96: The Candidate's Briefing Book</h2>
<b><A HREF="/heritage">The Heritage Foundation</a></b>
</center><p>
<h3>Chapter 14 - Additional Information</h3>
<center>
Return to <A HREF="chpt14.html">Chapter 14</a> | <a href="tblcon.html">Table of Contents</a></center> 
<P>
<a href = "#frustrating">Frustrating the Electorate: The Balanced Budget Amendment</a><br>
<a href = "#crime">Crime in Philadelphia</a><br>
<a href = "#demise">The Demise of Federalism</a><p>
<a name = "frustrating">FRUSTRATING THE ELECTORATE: THE BALANCED BUDGET AMENDMENT</a>
<p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
	The experience of the campaign for a balanced budget amendment is a clear demonstration of Washington's resistance to reform and its ability to outmaneuver the public. Despite overwhelming public support for an amendment to the Constitution to require Congress to balance the budget, Congress repeatedly has refused to send one to the states for ratification.
<p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;	In 1983, when a national movement to call a constitutional convention for the specific purpose of proposing such an amendment appeared within striking distance of the 34 states required, the congressional leadership finally moderated its long opposition and allowed a proposal for a balanced budget amendment to move through the legislative bureaucracy. This move succeeded in its primary purpose of killing the possibility of a convention, but the leadership still faced the problem of allowing a vote on a popular issue that it did not want enacted. Adroit behind-the-scenes maneuvering was necessary to allow Members who did not want to see an amendment pass, but for political reasons did not want to be seen as voting against such an amendment, to have it both ways.
<p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;	This effort to prevent a successful vote continued throughout the 1980s and into the 1990s as the debt mounted and the voters increasingly demanded a balanced budget. The most egregious example was the 1994 vote on an amendment proposed by Senator Paul Simon (D-IL), which appeared to have the 67 Senate votes needed for passage. To stop this measure, the Senate leadership introduced a competing proposal of their own design. They knew this version had no chance of passage, and that was its main attraction: Its real purpose was to split the vote and thereby deny either version a sufficient majority. In this way, Senators who really opposed a balanced budget amendment could portray themselves as favoring an amendment, and even go on record as voting for one, because they were assured that none would pass. Such maneuvers are common, and the people, repeatedly frustrated in their demands but with little evidence as to who exactly is responsible, are left to wonder what really happened.
<p>
<center><hr width=50%></center>
<p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<a name = "crime">In Philadelphia</a>, federal judge Norma Shapiro prevents local judges from detaining many violent defendants before trial by prohibiting them from considering the defendant's prior criminal record, mental health history, or drug dependency. The federal court also prevents any pre-trial detention for such "non-violent" crimes as stalking, carjacking, robbery with a baseball bat, burglary, drug dealing, vehicular homicide, manslaughter, terrorist threats, or weapons violations. Judges in Philadelphia are prohibited from forcing defendants to appear at trial, and the city now has 50,000 fugitives from justice. Instead of being in jail, these individuals have gone on to commit numerous other crimes. Between 1994 and June 1995, Philadelphia police rearrested 9,732 of these criminals (previously released under federal court orders) for 79 murders, 959 robberies, 2,215 drug deals, 701 burglaries, 2,748 thefts, 90 rapes, 14 kidnapping charges, 1,113 assaults, 264 gun-law violations, and 127 drunk-driving incidents.

<p>
<center><hr width=50%></center>
<p>

<a name="demise"<b>THE DEMISE OF FEDERALISM</b></a>
<p><b>1913</b> The 16th Amendment to the Constitution removes restrictions on Congress's ability to levy income taxes directly on the population. In 1914, federal income taxes accounted for less than one-fourth of 1 percent of the average American family's income. In 1994, over 24 percent of family income went to pay federal taxes.
<p><b>1913</b> The 17th Amendment to the Constitution mandates the direct election of Senators by the people, instead of by state legislatures. As a result, the states lose their role in national policymaking and their ability to carry out their constitutional role of checking and balancing the national government.
<p><b>1933-1945</b> New Deal legislation greatly increases the power and reach of the national government, but states and local governments retain many of their traditional functions. Waging World War II expands central government and solidifies Washington's ability to control the economy.
<p><b>1937</b> President Franklin Roosevelt threatens to overcome the Supreme Court's resistance to the expansion of federal power by packing the Court with additional members who support his agenda. In response to this threat, the Court acquiesces to most New Deal legislation by declaring many constitutional restraints null and void and dramatically expanding the powers granted to Washington by the Constitution. 
<p><b>1938</b> The Fair Labor Standards Act federalizes most worker-management relations in the U.S.
<p><b>1941</b> In United States v. Darby, the Supreme Court says the 10th Amendment is only a "truism" and "nothing more than declaratory," and denotes no constraints that the federal government need heed.
<p><b>1942</b> In Wickard v. Filburn, the Supreme Court removes virtually all limits on the federal government's power to regulate the economy by upholding the fines levied against an Ohio farmer for growing non-commercial wheat for his own use. The Court rules that Washington has the right to regulate any activity that may affect interstate commerce, including activity wholly confined to a private farm.
<p><b>1960s</b> The War on Poverty and other welfare projects vastly expand federal programs and funding throughout the economy and society.
<p><b>1985</b> In Garcia v. SAMTA, the Supreme Court rules that state and local agencies must follow national labor standards. The Court disposes of the remnants of federalism by saying that the states' interests are fully represented by the Senate, and thus that any law duly enacted by Congress automatically has the states' consent.
<p><b>1960s</b> In a series of controversial decisions, the Supreme Court overturns and rewrites whole sections of long-established law in the name of expanded individual rights, dramatically expanding the power of the federal courts to reshape society by undermining law enforcement and public order, removing religion from public life, erasing all restrictions on the power of Congress vis--vis the states and society, rewriting state constitutions, taking over state and local administrations, imposing racial quotas, and so forth.
<p><b>1994</b> The Supreme Court decides in U.S. Term Limits v. Thornton that the people have no right to set term limits on elected federal officials.
<p><b>1995</b> In U.S. v. Lopez, in a five-to-four decision, the Supreme Court uses the 10th Amendment to restrict federal power for the first time in six decades, although it is still uncertain to what extent this decision will limit Congress's power under the Commerce Clause.
<p>
<center><B><A HREF="chpt13.html">Previous Chapter</A> | <A HREF="chpt15.html">Next Chapter</A> | <A HREF="tblcon.html">Table of Contents</A> | <a href="/heritage">The Heritage Foundation</a> </B>
</center>
</BODY>
</HTML>
