<TITLE>INSTITUTE FOR CHILDREN</TITLE>


<H2><CENTER>INSTITUTE FOR CHILDREN</CENTER></H2>

<H3><CENTER>CURRENT PROGRAMS - SUMMER 1995</CENTER></H3>


<P>The <B>INSTITUTE FOR CHILDREN, INC.</B> creates and promotes innovative 
policies on foster care and adoption in America. What makes these 
policies "innovative" is a shift of focus away from building 
bureaucracies and toward helping children. The well-being of many 
thousands of youngsters depends on such innovation: across the nation 
50,000 children who could be adopted today are languishing in state-run 
foster care. The Institute for Children, a private, charitable organization, 
is reshaping foster care and adoption to make sure every child has a 
permanent, loving home.


<P>
<UL>
<LI>The Institute for Children is advising leaders. The Institute' s 
starting-point strategy plan, "What a Governor Can Do to Make Foster 
Care and Adoption Work," was one of the driving forces behind Governor 
William Weld' s November 1993 initiative, Assignment Adoption - A Home 
for Every Child.
</UL>
<I>The initiative has expedited adoption for many Massachusetts children: 
the number of 	foster child adoptions 
in the state has increased by 47% in one year, from 725 in 1993 to 
1,068 in 1994. The plan is now being studied in other states.
</I> 
<P>
<UL>
<LI>The Institute is extending its reach to governors across the nation and 
 to federal leaders, including members of the U.S. Senate, as today's 
 policy makers launch adoption and foster care reform.
<P>
<LI>The Institute is addressing urgent questions about foster care in its 
upcoming report, "21 Questions on Foster Care," to be co-published with 
the Dallas-based National Center for Policy Analysis.
<P>
<LI>The Institute is creating blueprints for change. With the Reason 
Foundation (Los Angeles), the Institute will soon co-publish 
"Private-sector approaches to foster care," a how-to guide for state 
and local governments. The guide assesses the results of model programs 
in five states.
<P>
<LI>The Institute for Children is changing the rules that keep children in 
foster care for too long. The Institute is working with the Institute for 
Justice, a public interest litigation group in Washington, D.C., to develop 
targeted lawsuits brought on behalf of foster children who are legally free 
to be adopted yet -- because of regulatory and practice barriers -- are 
forced to spend months or even years waiting for permanent adoptive families.
<P>
<LI>The Institute' s president, Conna Craig, has been asked by a prominent 
publisher to write a book on foster care in America. The book will examine 
the history, scope, complexities, outcomes and costs of state-run substitute 
care. The purpose of the book is to add depth to the debate on how to best 
care for America' s parentless children and, ultimately, to spark the types 
of policy changes that will wrest children from long-term state care and 
allow them to grow up in permanent families.
</UL>

<P>
<I>The Institute for Children, Inc. is a 5O1(c)(3) nonprofit, charitable organization founded in March 1993.</I>

<P>
18 BRATTLE STREET CAMBRIDGE, MASSACHUSETTS 02138 USA	TELEPHONE 617  491-4614	FACSIMILE 617 491-4673

