<html>
<title>Correspondence - Policy Review - Mar-Apr 96 - Heritage</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg"><img src="/heritage/p_review/mail.gif" align=left><CENTER>

<B>CORRESPONDENCE</B>
<HR><P><P><B><I>Policy Review: The Journal of American Citizenship</I><BR>
March-April 1996, Number 76</b>
</center><p>
<center><b>Citizenship AmeriCorps Style</b></center>
<p>To the Editor:<br>&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;Contrary to John Walters ("<a href="/heritage/p_review/jan96/walt.html">Clinton's AmeriCorps Values</a>," Jan.-Feb. 1996), AmeriCorps is a successful program that reinvigorates the principle of citizenship. Consider AmeriCorps's work with Birmingham AIDS Outreach (BAO) in Birmingham, Alabama.
<P>&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;Birmingham has been hit disproportionately hard by the AIDS epidemic, particularly the black heterosexual community. Sufferers have gone without care and have been forced to go to emergency rooms -- at  the expense of the state -- for care that can easily be provided at home.
<P>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;A proposal written by community organizations called for a team of individuals to provide in-home respite care for end-stage AIDS patients. Volunteers were needed to fill eight- to 10-hour shifts around the clock. The need overwhelmed an already substantial volunteer base, but volunteers from AmeriCorps answered the call.
<P>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;The BAO/AmeriCorps program paid a living allowance to its volunteers for the same reason that elected officials are paid: They were providing a public service to our country. In doing so, volunteers incurred an opportunity cost that would have otherwise precluded them from volunteering. For example, several BAO participants were mothers who had worked their way off welfare and were trying to finance a college education.<P>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;The proposal was not written by bureaucrats but by a coalition of clergymen, citizens, nonprofit organizations, medical professionals, and businessmen. The local coalition designed its own policies and mechanisms concerning implementation and care delivery.<P>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;The BAO program will save state and the federal government close to $2 million over its initial investment by allowing patients to die at home rather than in a hospital at the expense of Medicaid. It is a clear example of the AmeriCorps mission: to build partnerships between public and private agencies in order to rebuild America.
<P>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;It is a shame that Walters misunderstands the intentions behind the AmeriCorps program and the citizenship it embraces. While it would be nice if people could always solve their own problems, let's step off the ideological pedestal for a moment to realize that not everyone can. Citizens should be able to take care of one another in times of need. Feeding, bathing, and befriending a person dying of AIDS is neither a meaningless task nor a job deserving of only a meager living allowance, yet it has to be done. AmeriCorps makes it possible for people, welfare recipient and business executive alike, to do it -- to embrace true citizenship.<P>
<b>Kyle E. Kimball<br>Cambridge, Mass.</b><P><b>John Walters</b> responds:<P>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;Kimball assumes that just because AmeriCorps volunteers are doing good things that the program merits federal funding. A program that spends $500 million a year should produce results. But it is the unintended consequences of such programs that are often more significant -- witness the waste in the Medicaid program Kimball is proud to have corrected through his AmeriCorps program.
<P>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;Good deeds would not disappear if federal funding for AmeriCorps were eliminated. What civic leaders may have accomplished with federal dollars in Birmingham, countless private, religious, and charitable groups throughout America are achieving without federal assistance. One lesson from Birmingham is clear: AmeriCorps has taught people at the grass roots to look to Washington -- not their local communities -- for assistance.<p><center><b>Common-Sense Criminology</b></center>
<p>To the Editor:<br>As a former public defender, I agree whole-heartedly with John J. DiIulio's argument in "<a href="/heritage/p_review/fall95/thiuli.html">Arresting Ideas</a>" (Fall 1995). If a criminal thinks he will be caught committing a crime, he will be less likely to commit that crime.
<P>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;This law-breaking mentality lies within every reader. Do you accelerate when you are driving over the speed limit and spot a patrol car? If you don't, is it because you've just realized speeding is illegal or because you fear being caught?
<P>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;With the exception of psychopaths and the slow-witted, most people, including criminals, will not break the law if they think they will be caught. Criminals rely in part on sights and sounds when calculating the likelihood of their capture. A thug doesn't mug a person inside a police station, next to a patrol car, or when he hears a siren, even if it may be an ambulance.<P>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;In addition, criminals weigh the benefits of committing a crime against the costs they will incur if caught. A criminal is more likely to pass a forged check for $50 than commit armed robbery in a homeless shelter. As the length of a criminal's potential incarceration increases, a criminal is less likely to commit a crime.<p>
<b>Dan Coburn<br>Hamilton College<br>Clinton, N.Y.</b><P><center><b>Incorporation Intended</b></center>
<P>To the Editor:<br>I read with great dismay Rep. Bob Dornan's view of the Constitution ("<a href="/heritage/p_review/jan96/preserv.html#dornan">Preserve, Protect, Defend</a>," Jan.-Feb. 1996). Dornan articulates three constitutional fallacies which must be addressed.
<P>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;First, Dornan's essay is entitled "Government by Judiciary." This title aptly describes Dornan's incorrect view that judicial action that protects the precious liberties and fundamental rights of American citizens is merely an intrusion upon the "rights" of politicians. But in reality it is the job of the judiciary to stand astride the political branches, and majorities in general, to ensure that their actions are consistent with the basic constitutional guarantees granted to each individual citizen. In the end, Dornan's diatribe merely inflames the base bigotry directed towards those citizens who have been forced to seek judicial protection for their most basic rights: women, racial minorities, religious dissenters, and homosexuals.
<P>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;Second, Dornan asserts that the loss of federalism is the price America has paid for the end of slavery. This view presumes that federalism is incompatible with a structure of substantive constitutional restraint upon each level of government. Dornan apparently believes that the Thirteenth, Fourteenth, and Fifteenth Amendments repealed federalism. On the contrary, they perfected the American experiment by establishing the protection of individual rights as the primary responsibility of each level of government found in the federalist system.
<P>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;Third, Dornan concludes that the principle of incorporation should be repealed. What would this mean in practice? Well, consider that the Supreme Court has concluded that the Fourteenth Amendment incorporates the protections of the First, Third, Fourth, Fifth, Seventh, and Eighth Amendments "against" the states. In practice, therefore, each state must respect such basic principles as free speech, freedom of religion, freedom of association, the right to petition the government for a redress of grievances, and the prohibition against cruel and unusual punishment.
<P>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;In Dornan's constitutional universe, however, states and localities would be free to infringe upon religious liberty, free speech, or any other rights protected by the principle of incorporation. That most states and localities would not choose to infringe upon these rights is immaterial; the mere fact that these political entities would be capable of doing so is tantamount to concluding that Americans would be slaves to their government.<P>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;Contrary to sentiments expressed by the mythmakers who oppose judicial protection for individual rights, the framers of the Fourteenth Amendment intended the principle of incorporation to be expounded, and enforced, by the Supreme Court. Senator Howard, a Framer, declares that the Fourteenth Amendment's protections encompass "the personal rights guaranteed and secured by the first eight amendments of the Constitution" and that "the great objective" of the Fourteenth Amendment was to "compel [the states] at all times to respect these great fundamental guarantees."<P>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;In direct contrast to the false contentions of absolute-majoritarian state interventionists, Howard forcefully asserts that these protections "are secured to the citizen solely as a citizen of the United States and as a party in their courts." It is clear that the misguided advocates of absolute "judicial restraint" in areas of fundamental rights and liberties have blamed the messenger (judges) for the message (constitutional protection of individual rights).<P>
<b>Joe Mitchell<br>Virginia Polytechnic Institute<br>Blacksburg, Va.</b><p><center><b>Stigma, Not Spirit</b></center>
<p>To the Editor:<br>
In his <a href="/heritage/p_review/jan96/letter.html">"Welcome"</a> to the new <I>Policy Review</I> (Jan.-Feb. 1996), Adam Meyerson says, "The root cause of crime is spiritual, a hardening of the heart that makes a man or woman indifferent to the rights of others." Maybe.
<P>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;When children have little or no parental guidance it does not take a genius to expect trouble. When a delinquent is not reprehended, publicly rebuked, humiliated, recidivism can be expected.
<P>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;The root cause of crime is the lack of stigma attached to it. Spirituality is not needed to lead a moral life.
<P>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;You want your new format to build a bridge to liberals whose policies have failed. This is like trying to run a business by committee. If conservatives have the guts and wisdom to find new approaches to adult and juvenile crime, let them stand up and be counted. Nothing works better than success.
<p><b>James L. Robson<br>LaBelle, Fla.</b><p><center><b>Kind Words</b></center><p>
To the Editor:<br>
Bravo for adopting a "historic new mission: to restore the tradition of American citizenship" in the newly designed <I>Policy Review</I> (<a href="/heritage/p_review/jan96/letter.html">"Welcome,"</a> Jan.-Feb.). We are at a crossroads, or maybe close to a point of no return, having lost our sense of citizenship and our understanding of rights and responsibilities. Historians will look at the past 30 years and wonder how a nation founded on the principles of Washington and Jefferson -- how "one nation, under God" --  could have become so depraved.
<P>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;Current films based on the writings of Jane Austen remind us how far we have come from common sense and decency. It is wonderful to see these films well-attended and observe young people who seem to wonder how we have strayed so far.<P>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;The time is ripe. Thank you for supporting the American family with educational material and examples of people taking positive steps to make a difference for all of us. Our children are searching for role models, and you can provide them.<p>
<b>Joseph B. Famme<br>Arlington, Va.</b><p>To the Editor:<br>
I am writing to compliment you on the Jan.-Feb. issue of <I>Policy Review: The Journal of American Citizenship</I>. I particularly enjoyed your <a href="/heritage/p_review/jan96/preserv.html">presidential symposium</a> ("Preserve, Protect & Defend"). For the last 50 years, too many people have come to believe that the president's responsibility to the Constitution consists of appointing conscientious judges to the bench. That is only one part of the executive's responsibility. The president should also use the bully pulpit to fight for his constitutional vision, veto unconstitutional bills, and refuse to enforce unconstitutional legislation that is already on the books. That is what the oath of office is all about!<p>
<b>Timothy Lynch<br><a href="http://www.cato.org">Cato Institute</a><br>Washington, D.C.</b><P>To the Editor:<br>I have been a reader of <I>Policy Review</I> for more than a year. I recently received the Jan.-Feb. 1996 issue and enjoy the new format and content.<P>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;Its <a href="/heritage/p_review/prstate.html">"Statement of Purpose"</a> and <a href="/heritage/p_review/jan96/letter.html">"Letter to Our Readers"</a> excite me and give me hope. We all know that our government, in its desire to help, has grown to hurt -- that "we the people" need to do it better through the wonderful liberties of our Constitution.
<P>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;This publication is needed. I look forward to the wealth of information future issues will surely contain.<p>
<b>Michael A. McKinley<br>Aurora, Colo.</b>
<p>

